metadata.name: Subdivisions #81
metadata.description:
As an artist with a background in engineering, I have always been a fan of technical drawings.
Architectural sketches and renderings fascinate me with their ability to visualize the conceptual.

I create generative art for the same reason - to reveal the beauty in an algorithm.

This project represents the division of space using techniques that, for me, call to mind sitting
at a drafting table, straight edge in hand, imagining what might be possible.

You can export a high resolution PNG (5000x5000) by pressing the 'e' key.

Twitter: @jeffpalmer
https://jpalmer.dev

metadata.name: Oxygen #65
metadata.description:
Oxygen makes strange forms of life thrive even in the darkest of places.

This is a generative piece using curated randomness to create textures, generate distortion fields, simulate growth and create compositions.

The work is best viewed in high resolution, but due to the time it takes to render, the preview image is capped to only 1000 pixels in height. You can change the resolution by pressing keys

- 'm' for medium  (height=2000px)
- 'l' for large (height=3500px)
- 'x' for extra large (height=5000px) 

outputs. 

Press 's' to save the output as a PNG file.

For even larger outputs, you can open the work in live mode and append the text '?size=10000' to the URL. Here, you can change the number (10000) to the desired height in pixels. 

Please note, that a very high-resolution image may take a very long time to render and some browsers are not able to save the image. However, even a 10000 pixels tall outputs have been generated during testing.

metadata.name: Luminaries #55
metadata.description:
There is no light without dark.

Luminaries is a study in symmetry, contrast and flow, with a palette inspired by the twelve full moon names. Owning a Luminary enables you to request a signed print for an additional fee. 

You can learn more about features and prints at: https://www.phaust.art/luminary

Each Luminary is composed of moons in various phases. Their layout derived from a handful of geometries. They contrast with their surroundings: filled with glittering stars, inky strokes or solid colour. 

Backgrounds can split along lines of symmetry – with dark and light contrasting as strokes seamlessly flow across the two halves. 

Luminaries are alive. They’re in retrograde once a month, a day in which you’ll see yours in a new light.

------

Collection Size: 158. One for each of the confirmed moons in our solar system.

Palettes: 12 + 1. One for each of the full moons plus a rarer secret palette: Wolf, Snow, Worm, Pink, Flower, Strawberry, Buck, Sturgeon, Harvest, Hunter, Beaver, Cold, ????.

Retrograde: day of the month that your Luminary will change for one day only.

S: to save at high resolution. 

Prints: request from https://www.phaust.art/luminary

metadata.name: Crosswalk Monsoon #285
metadata.description:
The story behind this collection is that there isn't really a story behind this collection. It is the result of play, tinkering, and curiosity.

One of the beautiful things about generative art is how we can achieve drastically different results simply by modifying a few parameters or lines of code. As my first release here on fxhash was 'Sabler', it felt fitting that my release for #fxhashturnsone would itself be a modified version of that 'Sabler' algorithm, albeit giving drastically different results.

It is notable for the fact that this is perhaps my most 'chaotic' collection yet, letting go of carefully considered proportions, angles and positioning and here leaving that in the hands of the computer. In a way, this simple act represents several design decisions I never would have imagined myself making a year ago, highlighting my growth as a generative artist over the past year.

It is also a reflection of the inspiration gained from many of the artists and boundary-pushers in the space that each time unlock and encourage creations beyond the immediate comfort zone. For that, this is a 'Thank You' to all of you.

With that, here's to many more years of generative beauty and inspiration on fxhash and beyond.

As with previous collections, I highly recommend viewing the images at full size and savouring the details and the chaos up close. Pressing 'S' will save a 6000 x 6000 px PNG file.

50% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation.

metadata.name: September #186
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: Over the Air #296
metadata.description:
During the last couple of decades, over the air television signals and antennas switched to digital, bringing with them a new form of static and distortion as the signal is broken up. "Over the Air" is inspired by these digital distortions, incorporating aspects of them into the same grid-like structure seen on the television. Additional patterns are combined in the grid with these distortions to create the final artwork.

Patterns for the individual blocks in the grid are divided into categories, and various amounts are picked for each work, with dozens of possible mixtures. Patterns can flow in different directions across the varied canvases. Distribution of these patterns across the grid varies from work to work, providing for different feels as they bunch together or spread apart.

metadata.name: BLOCK PARTY #79
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm exploring isometric grids and recursive divisions with an emphasis on contrasting colors.

A random rectange division is so simple yet creates vastly different and interesting outputs.

An isometric grid provides a unique perspective to the recursion giving each piece a certain depth and contrast.

When does chaotic randomness become beauty and what interesting patterns may emerge?

Press 's' in live mode to save image. Best viewed after save.

* Original code by Matt Lehoullier with p5.js

metadata.name: Sparsely Populated Grid #159
metadata.description:
“Sparsely Populated Grid” is the result of an architect’s fascination with Cartographies and a crypto-enthusiast love for Neo Punk aesthetics. The first sketch, drawn by hand with Procreate, was made in October 2021.

This is an exploration on the field of Generative Cartographies, an abstract diagrammatic representation of a randomly generated area within the virtual IPFS world. Everything starts with an GRID of varying sizes and angles, subsequently POPULATED by a random number of forms. But, how to populate the grid? SPARSELY, of course, with just the right amount of superpositions.

The algorithm produces varying compositions of fourteen different forms, with seven possible mixes and ten colour palettes. Movement, made possible by its generative digital nature, follows sinusoidal patterns, as if the forms breathed and danced to an unheard music.

Besides, they never forget to celebrate birthdays.


// INTERACTIVITY

- CLICK or SPACEBAR to stop movement.
- UP and DOWN ARROWS to Disable/Enable graphic elements such as texts (wink).
- LEFT and RIGHT ARROWS (when stopped) to Move frames back and forth.
- Press 1 for a low-res PNG.
- Press 2 for a medium-res PNG (3x).
- Press 3 for a hi-res PNG (6x).
- Press G for Glitch (low-res).
- Press P for PixelArt (low-res).

If you want a different resolution, you can also add ?&res=xxx to the url to get your desired output. Then simply Right-Click SAVE the canvas -- experimental

metadata.name: Study of Geometry Composition #55
metadata.description:
Avant-garde art became a genre of its own during the 20th century. It was popularized by Suprematist, Constructivist, Bauhaus, and mid-century artists seeking a strong break from the traditional feathered painting that has characterized art through the centuries.

Hard-edge painters, who used masking tape to create sharp lines and edges, were especially important to the development of mid-century art, from Minimalism to Pop Art. The evolution of the line and its use in fine art applications skyrocketed during this period, and the art world has never looked back.

In the years that followed, artists broke new ground with lines, traditional geometric shapes, texture, and color. In particular, the work of the late Venezuelan artist Carlos Cruz-Diez has been a major influence on my work.

In my opinion, geometry is among the most powerful forms of graphic expression available to the contemporary artist.

by Daniel Oropeza
Tw: @ferdoropeza

metadata.name: Zoombie #59
metadata.description:
This series concept was inspired by my previous series, "Nekombies", but this time I have added more animal elements to create even more interesting combinations.

The theme of the series is "Zoombie", which is a concept that combines animal and zombie elements. In this series, I combine traditional zombie images with various animal images to create a novel feeling. I deeply love zombie culture, so I have combined this concept with my creativity to create this unique series.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
这个系列的概念是源自我之前的一系列作品“Nekombies”，而这次我将更多动物元素加入到作品中，希望能够为大家带来更多有趣的组合。

作品的主题是“Zoombie”，它是一个将动物和僵尸元素融合在一起的概念。在这个系列中，我将传统的僵尸形象与各种不同的动物形象相结合，
制造出一种新奇的感觉。我深深地爱着僵尸文化，因此将这个概念与我的创意结合，创造出了这个独特的系列。



It is an Image compostion made using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool. 
Created by Unlimited Space✨無限宇宙🪐 | https://twitter.com/Unlimitez666

metadata.name: Knockout #116
metadata.description:
An exploration of screen printing techniques and how these effects can be achieved in generative work. The halftone effect works by placing very small dots next to each other to give the illusion of new shades and hues. Each Knockout samples three colors for the main composition and runs small sections of the canvas back through the machine after shuffling the base palette. The secondary passes vary in size, creating interesting emergent patterns on the overlap.

Press 's' in live view to save a .png

Built and tested with Chrome on Apple silicon. Some outputs may take up to 20s on slower machines.

Created with p5.js and chroma.js
